  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Farewell to the Judge of Andong, Using the Rhyme Scheme of Bao Zhao's 'Song of the Eastern Gate'
  author: Lee Gyeong-dong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The parted strings cry out—unbearable to hear,
    The urgent notes find no harmony to answer.
    The parted cup cannot bring drunkenness,
    Yet when drained, tears overflow like wine.

    Lay down the cup, set aside the lute—
    Let us speak one final word together.
    A man of worth knows what matters and what does not;
    Our sorrow does not rest in separation alone.

    Your parents dwell ten thousand li away,
    And autumn steals upon their bending years.
    To nourish them is the child's sacred duty—
    Not even one meal have I forgotten to provide.
    To cast off office—would this betray filial love?
    Yet to stay or go, the heart cannot decide.

    I remain at home to attend their twilight hours,
    Gazing southward till my eyes grow cold.
    Yesterday the commission arrived from above—
    Andong Judge, and joy breaks upon my face.

    Return now to your post with steadfast purpose:
    Loyalty and filial piety are not two separate paths.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Bao Zhao was a celebrated poet of the Song Dynasty whose 'Song of the Eastern Gate' (東門行) was a model for farewell poetry in East Asia.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem skillfully weaves themes of separation, filial duty, and official service, culminating in the insight that loyalty to the state and devotion to parents need not conflict.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of parted strings and emptied cups evokes both music and wine-sharing as traditional elements of farewell ceremonies.
